The "Fine, We'll Do It Ourselves" Cooperative License (FWDIOL) Version 1.0

        Copyright (C) [2024] [InterCooperative Network]
    (Because, apparently, we're also part-time lawyers now.)


Welcome to the license that acknowledges we all thought we could just make stuff and share it, but then reality called. It's like hosting a potluck and realizing you need rules because Kevin always brings store-bought chips and calls it a day.

Preamble:
In the spirit of making the world a slightly better place—one line of code at a time—this license is our collective pinky promise. It's designed for those who have the audacity to believe in collaboration, transparency, and not letting the pursuit of profit bulldoze the digital commons we’re all planting.

1. Sharing Is Caring, But Let's Not Be Naive About It
    • 1.1 You’re free to use, tweak, and share this masterpiece or its derivatives. However, if you’re turning a profit, remember the little people (us). And by remember, we mean in a tangible, "show me the        money" kind of way, not just sending good vibes.

    • 1.2 Repackaging this without substantial changes and selling it is frowned upon. That’s like claiming you made the wine when all you did was buy it at the store. Don’t be that person.

2. Honesty Is The Best Policy
    • 2.1 If you find a treasure map (a.k.a. a bug), share it. If you’ve got the shovel and know-how to dig it up (fix it), even better. Let’s keep the field free of pitfalls for the next treasure hunter.

    • 2.2 Contributions are welcome, but let's not pretend a sprinkle of salt is a gourmet meal. Quality matters. If you contribute, it’s under the same "don’t be a jerk" conditions.

3. The Commons: It's Not Just a Fancy Word
    • This isn’t just software; it’s a digital commune. And in this commune, we’re aiming for less "corporate dystopia" and more "utopian dream." Sure, the latter might be as achievable as flawless code, but     we aim high.

4. Warranties Are Like Unicorns
    • Here’s the thing: This software is as-is. If it breaks, don’t look at us. If it works, we’re geniuses. But really, it’s a communal effort, so if something goes sideways, it’s on all of us to pitch in and fix it.

5. Don’t Sue Us, Join Us
    • If something in this software offends you, shocks you, or even mildly irritates you, remember: you’re part of this too. Don’t litigate, innovate. Or at least open a dialogue. We’re all in this mess together.

In conclusion, this license is our way of saying we’re trying to do something good here. Let’s not get lost in the legalese but remember the heart of the matter: building something together, for the common good, without losing our sense of humor or our minds.
